{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16244"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16244"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.38,0.09,0.11,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8935"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115391"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8935"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16244"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97394"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8625"},{"type":"tags","id":"9847"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22348"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115391"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring fetal development, several vascular structures undergo significant changes after birth to form adult anatomical structures. One such structure is the ligamentum teres of the liver. This is formed from the remnant of certain fetal vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following forms the ligamentum teres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ductus arteriosus","Ductus venosus","Left cardinal vein","Umbilical artery","Umbilical vein"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eumbilical vein\u003C/strong\u003E carries oxygenated blood from the placenta to the fetus during development. After birth, it obliterates and forms the ligamentum teres (round ligament) within the falciform ligament of the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options form different adult structures. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eductus venosus\u003C/strong\u003E becomes the ligamentum venosum, whilst the \u003Cstrong\u003Eductus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E becomes the ligamentum arteriosum. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eumbilical artery\u003C/strong\u003E becomes the medial umbilical ligament, and the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft cardinal vein\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to the formation of the coronary sinus. These changes occur as part of the transition from fetal to adult circulation after birth when the placental circulation is no longer needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ligamentum teres (round ligament) of the liver is the remnant of the fetal umbilical vein.","The umbilical vein carries oxygenated blood from the placenta to the fetal liver and heart during development.","After birth, the umbilical vein obliterates to form a fibrous cord called the ligamentum teres within the falciform ligament."],"references":["Spurway J, Logan P, Pak S. The development, structure and blood flow within the umbilical cord with particular reference to the venous system. Australas J Ultrasound Med. 2012 Aug;15(3):97-102. doi: 10.1002/j.2205-0140.2012.tb00013.x. Epub 2015 Dec 31. PMID: 28191152; PMCID: PMC5025097.","O\u0027Donnell JM, Pritchard M, Salas AP, Singh PJ. The ligamentum teres-its increasing importance. J Hip Preserv Surg. 2014 Jul 30;1(1):3-11. doi: 10.1093/jhps/hnu003. PMID: 27011796; PMCID: PMC4765261.","Martin RL, McDonough C, Enseki K, Kohreiser D, Kivlan BR. CLINICAL RELEVANCE of the LIGAMENTUM TERES: A LITERATURE REVIEW. Int J Sports Phys Ther. 2019 Jun;14(3):459-467. doi: 10.26603/ijspt20190459. PMID: 31681504; PMCID: PMC6816302.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97394"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16244"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97394"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:38:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:41:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8935"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115391"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji"